<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-311-476  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 311 476.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 3 1990 v4 n13 p67(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Thesaurus builders turn to Mac. (Lexical Technologies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cohen, Raines.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Lexical Technologies is using Hypercard as the basis for itsmetathesaurus to help researchers and physicians cross-referencemedial terms.andP;  The project is sponsored by the US National Libraryof Medicine (NLM), which is trying to create the Unified MedicalLanguage System information retrieval system.andP;  Lexical has itsmetathesaurus on a set of HyperCard stacks totalling about130Mbytes, with more than 40,000 entries on 106,000 cards.andO;Lexical is attempting to use existing technology andcomputer-readable publications in the project.andP;  The process beginswith an indexing engine to collate different definitions ofidentical terms and link them among related terms within a singlesource document and among different sources.andP;  Human editorscorrect computer-generated links and create new ones the computercould not catch.andP;  MetaCard will be published by the NLM during thethird quarter of 1990.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lexical Technologies Inc. (equipment and supplies).andO;Product:   HyperCard (Data base management system) (usage).andO;Topic:     United States. National Library of MedicineContractsThesauriMedical ResearchUnified Medical Language System (Information retrieval system)Information SystemsHypertext.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Raines CohenandM;Alameda, Calif.andP;  -- A small company working here on a federally fundedproject is stretching the limits of what can be done with HyperCard.andP;  LexicalTechnologies is developing a metathesaurus to help researchers and physicianscross-reference medical terms.andM;The metathesaurus is part of the Unified Medical Language System projectsponsored by the National Library of Medicine.andP;  Launched in 1986, the 10-yearprogram is designed to improve physicians' access to existing medicalinformation, including citation databases, clinical data such aspatient-record databases, and on-line services such as MEDLINE.andM;&quot;Roget (creator of Roget's International Thesaurus) was a physician,&quot; saidDavid Sherertz, president and CEO of Lexical Technologies.andP;  &quot;Medical termsare often used very differently in the literature than in clinical settings.andO;For instance, 'ventilation' means building air circulation in MEDLINE's MESH(Medical Subject Headings index), but patient records use it to meanproviding air to the lungs of a human being.andP;  The trick is to provide theconnection so someone using one term can get to another.&quot;andM;A metathesaurus goes further by combining and cross-indexing many thesauri toform a more powerful reference work, Sherertz said.andP;  Lexical's MetaCard, aset of HyperCard stacks, brings all the related but disparate informationtogether to help find lexical variants, synonyms and various lexicons'preferred terms.andM;The company's strategy, Sherertz said, is to use existing technology andcomputer-readable publications in the project.andP;  Lexical's indexing enginecollates different definitions of identical terms and makes links amongrelated terms both within a single source document and among differentsources.andP;  Human editing polishes the work, correcting inappropriatecomputer-generated links and generating new, semantic ones.andM;Meta-1, the first version of Lexical's MetaCard, currently measures about 130Mbytes, with more than 40,000 entries spread over 106,000 cards.andP;  The data isbroken into a series of stacks to make finding data easier.andP;  Sherertz saidHyperCard and the company's proprietary indexing scheme add about a 25percent overhead to the raw data.andP;  MetaCard will be published on CD-ROM bythe National Library of Medicine in the third quarter of 1990.andM;Lexical's work on this project could apply in other fields as well, Sherertzsaid.andP;  Any field using &quot;structured text&quot; -- that is, any large,machine-readable set of information -- could take advantage of the company'stechniques.andM;Lexical Technologies is at 1000 Atlantic Ave., Suite 106, Alameda, Calif.andO;95401-1366; (415) 865-8500.andO;</TEXT></DOC>